text=:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages%0a:Expansion: ɪ versus i when g dropping%0a:Author: sathyas%0a:Original: [[Articles.EnglishG-droppin|EnglishG-droppin]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.caseywalker|caseywalker]]%0a:Section: E%0a:Completed: 03.04.2021 - 18:00%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-214427-845900#%0a* [-05.05.2021 - 14:44-] || TA_mason marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-214427-845900#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aA study from UPenn tested to see whether there was a actually a noticeable change in the [i] sound to [ɪ] when G dropping rather than just the nasal codas. To test the theory, they compared 9 native English speakers versus 10 Mandarin speakers (who have fluent or nearly fluent English) to see whether the notice the difference in the vowel sound. Mandarin speakers were chosen because Mandarin has alveolar and velar nasal codas as English does, however Mandarin does not have the lax [ɪ] phoneme. The correct answer for whether G dropping occurred was ruled by the majority answer of the English speakers. The results showed that the Mandarin speakers had noticeably lower classification accuracy, indicating that the variation in the ING pronunciation is more than solely the difference in nasal codas [n] vs [ŋ]. %0a%0aSource: https://www.ling.upenn.edu/~jiahong/publications/cn1.pdf%0a%0aAs a separate thing, I believe that G dropping is not prevalent in words like "bring" and "thing" since they have 1 syllable. Gerunds have at least two syllables because the ING is added to a root verb so G dropping is prevalent. Besides gerunds, words ending in ING with 2 or more syllables like "nothing" may experience G-dropping. I have no evidence for this but its just a theory.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_mason:)
